<DOC><DOCNO> AP880615-0251 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2330EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Heroin-Death     06-15 0201</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Heroin-Death,0207</SECOND><HEAD>Australian Woman, Thai Man Sentenced to Death For HeroinTrafficking</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An Australian woman and a Thai man weresentenced to death Wednesday for trafficking in 12 pounds of herointhe woman carried in her 14-month-old son's stroller.   The Bangkok Criminal Court reduced an earlier death sentenceagainst the woman's common law husband to life imprisonment afterhe admitted to heroin possession and cooperated with authorities.   Nola Blake; the man she lived with in suburban Sydney, PaulHudson; and Supoj Kittidejdamkern were arrested in January 1987 andcharged with possessing heroin with intention to sell.   Police said Ms. Blake and Hudson, who is also Australian,obtained the heroin from Supoj for sale in Australia.   Ms. Blake and Hudson, both 37, were arrested in front of adepartment store while pushing their son in a stroller thatcontained the heroin, police said. The baby was flown to Australiato be cared for by relatives in Sydney.   ``I knew it was coming. I knew it was coming,'' Ms. Blake saidafter the verdict, shaking her head as she walked from the courtback to jail.   Ms. Blake translated the verdict for Hudson, who appeared paleand shaken.</TEXT></DOC>